      "content": "If the tensile forces exceed the capacity of the steel rebar within the concrete, the concrete can crack or even fail. Here's what happens inside the material when the tension gets too high:\n\n1. Cracking: The first sign of failure is usually cracking. The concrete matrix, which is strong in compression but weak in tension, starts to crack under excessive tensile stress. These cracks can be small and hairline, or they can be large and visible, depending on the magnitude of the applied forces.\n\n2. Debonding: As the cracks widen, the bond between the concrete and the steel rebar can weaken. This is because the concrete matrix is no longer able to effectively transfer the tensile forces to the rebar. The steel rebar may still be intact, but the concrete around it is no longer able to support the load.\n\n3. Spalling: In some cases, the concrete may start to flake or spall off, especially near the surface. This occurs when the tensile forces cause the concrete to break apart, leaving behind a rough, uneven surface.\n\n4. Complete failure: If the tensile forces continue to increase, the concrete can eventually fail completely. This can result in large sections of the foundation or structure collapsing, posing a significant",
